post_text:
Great news! Santa Ynez Elementary is now able to serve FREE breakfast and lunch to all children ages 0-18 at the Santa Ynez Campus.

Starting today, any child age 18 or younger can receive a free lunch and breakfast. Lunch, and breakfast for the next day, are served from 11:45 a.m. to 12:45 p.m., Monday through Friday (school holidays excluded). Families with Solvang School students should plan to get lunch during a time that does not affect online learning. If your child attends Solvang School and plans to get a lunch, please make sure they are included in the morning lunch count taken at the 8:30 a.m. check-in/homeroom time.

When picking up a meal, masks and social distancing are required. Free lunch and breakfast will be offered until further notice.

#BobcatStrong

The California PBIS (Positive Behavioral Interventions and Supports) Coalition has just awarded College/Santa Ynez Elementary with the highest honor available this year, the Community Cares Medal!

Our entire staff has worked extremely hard over the past three years for this award, adopting and implementing several PBIS strategies district-wide and we are very proud to be the only school in Santa Barbara County to receive this recognition.

Way to go, Bobcats!

#BobcatStrong

post_text:
Congratulations to our very own Christie Ruelas (Mrs. R.) for being selected as the 2020 California's Classified School Employee of the Year in the Para-Educator and Instructional Assistance category!

Christie is a general education instructional aide on our campus as well as an English Language Development Aide. She is also our district's Lunch Program Coordinator, Homework Aide, PTO Treasurer, and she volunteers for our Wellness Program and LCAP Advisory Committee.

Those of us who are lucky enough to work and learn from Mrs. R. know that she is fun, encouraging, and a morale booster for all. Her dedication to our Bobcat students, families, and staff members is so appreciated and this award is very well deserved. We are all SO PROUD of you, Christie, and so happy to have you in our Bobcat family!

#BobcatStrong

To culminate the unit on ancient Egypt, the 6th grade students presented projects during their weekly Zoom meeting. For his Egypt Project, Devin used Minecraft to build replicas of ancient Egyptian architecture, including the temple Abu Simbel and the Pyramids of Giza. He then edited together a video of what he created. It took Devin almost two months of hard work and dedication to complete his project. Way to go above and beyond!

To watch the full video, click here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1iG0XAw-sFs

post_text:
Ten work samples from nine and ten year-old students to inspire a little #MotivationalMonday

These fourth graders were given the prompt:
Write an opinion paper on the best game ever invented.

Each day for a week, in Google Classroom, they spent 30 minutes drafting and revising their essays with grammar and spelling help from the teacher.

Mr. Haines and Mr. Bruemmer are very proud of these kids and the work they put in all school year to learn how to write the famous "Five Paragraph Essay".

Maurene Donner

**Important School Update**

Good afternoon,

In order to help with social distancing we are now recommending that students stay home from school on Monday, March 16th and Tuesday, March 17th leading up to the school closure on Wednesday, March 18th through Spring Break April 10th. If you are not able to find childcare and/or make other arrangements, school will be in session from 8:30 – 3:00.

Teachers will be in touch later this week with lessons/assignments for their students. In the meantime, you may find the resources below interesting:

Thanks,

Maurene Donner

Our 5th and 4th graders went to La Purisima Mission for a Student Learning History Day.

Groups of students got to interact with costumed docents and staff. Activities included corn grinding, rolling flour into dough, tortilla cooking, weaving, candle making, making a nail through blacksmithing, Chumash games, and learning all about the Mission grounds and buildings.

It was a beautiful day and the kids really enjoyed walking the grounds, hiking the trails, and all of the hands-on activities that brought the Mission to life!

Our 6th-8th grade AVID students had a fun and exciting day of learning at an LA Clippers game this week!

Panelists from the Clippers Organization responded to AVID students' questions about their education and pathways to a career they love in sports. Representatives from Sponsorships, Marketing, Entertainment, Social Media, and Graphic Design provided insight and inspiration for students following their passion.

Students who asked and answered questions got the opportunity to shoot a free throw on the court for a free Clippers t-shirt.

6th-8th graders then watched a nail-biter of a game as the Clippers came from behind to beat the Spurs 108-105.

post_text:
4th grade students spent the night this weekend on an 1830s replica tall ship, The Spirit of Dana Point. They role played as sailors traveling from Boston, around Cape Horn, and up to Santa Barbara to trade cow hides. Students learned about California history, how to tie special sailing knots, how to assemble and use pulley systems, the struggles of night watch, and a lot about working together as a team. The kids, and parents, all had a blast!

Thank you, Santa Barbara Maritime Museum, for sponsoring our class for the third year in a row!

Good morning, Bobcat Parents!

This evening (Thursday August 22, 2019) is Back to School Night.

The College campus (TK-K) program will be held from 5:00pm to 5:45 pm.

The Santa Ynez campus (grades 1-5) activities will begin at 6:00 pm. Grades 6-8 will begin at 6:45 pm.

This night is for parents only and you will be receiving lots of helpful information in regards to your child's class. You will have the opportunity to ask questions and get details regarding your student's schedule, upcoming school events, and much more.

PTO's membership drive will also be going on, so look for Mrs. Ruelas!

We hope to see you all there!

post_text: Mrs. Delman's 3rd-6th grade GATE classes recently completed a beautification and water-wise project with grant money received from the Tri-County Gate Consortium. Students researched the climate of Santa Ynez to help choose which plants can thrive here, along with the right type of soil. Lastly, students chose self-watering planter containers to help reduce plant rot and the need for plant waterings during the hot summer months. Great job, Bobcats!

post_text:
Mrs. Elliott's 3rd graders visited the Santa Barbara Botanical Gardens to learn about the native plants that can be found around our area. The native Chumash would use many of the plants for medicine, food, making homes, baskets, and boats. Local wildlife served as food and their skins were used for clothing and trade.

Afterwards, they enjoyed some ice skating at Ice In Paradise in Goleta. For many students, it was their first time ice skating and they braved slipping and sliding around the rink.

We want to thank Mrs. Elliott for putting this all together and wish her a speedy recovery! An extra special thank you to the parent chaperones: Mr. Rueff, Mr. Shomes, Mrs. Garcia, and Mrs. Toriche!

Afterwards, they enjoyed some ice skating at Ice In Paradise in Goleta. For many students, it was their first time ice skating and they braved slipping and sliding around the rink.

We want to thank Mrs. Elliott for putting this all together and wish her a speedy recovery! An extra special thank you to the parent chaperones: Mr. Rueff, Mr. Shomes, Mrs. Garcia, and Mrs. Toriche!

post_text: 4th, 5th, and 6th grade students traveled to the Santa Barbara County Mathematics Super Bowl today. A highlight was the team building challenge where students were asked to make a tower from newspaper, at least 12 inches tall, that holds the most weight. 5th grade had over 168 metal washers! The kids described their experience as "PE for the brain". Thank you to Mrs. Delman for her hard work and leadership in working with these brilliant young minds!
